@book{Parsons2018,
	abstract = {The ProsocialLearn project aims to create a new digital gaming genre that focuses on supporting children (aged 7 to 10 yrs) to acquire prosocial skills necessary for positive relationships, team working, trustworthiness and emotional intelligence (EI).
This Deliverable describes the third evaluation phase which focuses on the activities conducted in school conditions in order to evaluate children's behavioural and experiential responses to game play. The evaluation activities conducted in the UK, Greece, Italy and Spain and their findings are described and discussed. A total of 301 8 to 10-year-old children were involved in in-depth studies in the UK, Greece and Italy, with a further 73 children, aged 9-12 years, involved in less intensive data collection in Spain.
From the study in the UK, which involved 25 children, despite the absence of statistically significant difference, the small sample from Group 1 (n=12) showed increases in their self-perception median scores from Assessment T1 to Assessment T3, indicating a slight tendency towards higher self-perception ratings for these children after the PSL game play sessions. This was the group of children who played the PSL games for the longer period (4 weeks) compared to the comparison group (2 weeks) where no changes were found. Children's nomination of peers (sociometric data) also revealed some changes in a positive direction for some of the main categories (`Cooperative', `Popular' or `Good at school work') between Assessment T1 to Assessment T3.
From the study in Greece, which involved 185 children, the findings from the Strengths and Difficulties Questionnaire (prosocial domain) showed significant increases in teachers' ratings between the three points of assessment for all children. However, the ratings were slightly lower from Assessment T2 to Assessment T3, suggesting that the effect may not be very stable. This could also be test-retest reliability issue for the SDQ over short periods of time. In addition, there were slight differences with the sociometric data (peers' nomination), as the mean scores in specific categories (i.e. `Cooperative' or `Athletic') were higher between Assessment T1 to T2, suggesting some effect. Significant difference for the category of `Leader' during Assessment T1, T2 and T3 for Class 1, showed that children received higher nominations on this characteristic between the three points of assessment.
In the Italian study, which involved 91 children, we could not report on the findings from the prosocial domain of the SDQ. Nevertheless, children's self-perception scores for one of the schools (Orange) increased significantly from Assessment T1 to Assessment T3, suggesting that there was a positive effect on self-perceptions associated with playing the PSL games. The sociometric data (peer nominations) were analysed for only one class (out of four) due to time constraints, and revealed no significant differences.
Overall, there were some positive indications from prosocial measures in the UK, Greece and Italy that children benefitted prosocially from playing the PSL games. In some cases, these indications were based on teacher ratings of children's prosociality (SDQ for teachers), and in other cases based on children's ratings of themselves and others (Self-Perception Profile for Children, Peer Nomination form). In terms of usability and acceptability, the two games for which we have the most data are `Laika' and `Pushy Paddles'. Children really enjoyed their exposure to these games and appreciated the opportunities to work collaboratively with their peers. Teachers were also positive about these games and could see that children enjoyed them, while they provided useful feedback about how the games could be used for supporting learning in the classroom. Children also enjoyed the `Lost in Space' and `Tower Together' games in the Spanish study with less in-depth data collection. Although, teachers were less positive, mostly due to technical problems experienced when playing these games, overall, children and teachers accepted (most of) the games as enjoyable and valid tools that could be used in the classroom context to support children's learning.
