@phdthesis{Jensen2017,
	abstract = {The differences in results across research demonstrate that the social and psychological effects, positive or negative, of video games can be influenced by many variables, including play style and social context (Anderson et al., 2010; Ferguson \& Kilburn, 2010; Greitemeyer and Oswald, 2010; Ewoldsen et al., 2012). The purpose of this study was to determine if face-to-face game play (social context) would result in more prosocial behaviors in both cooperative as well as competitive game play (play style), as compared to online play. Participants played Mario Kart 8 in pairs competitively or cooperatively and online or face-to-face. Participants then played a game where each decided how many dimes to give to the other participant over ten trials in order to measure generosity. A 2x2 between-subjects factorial ANOVA was calculated for the mean number of dimes given to the other participant. Results showed that participants who played the Mario Kart 8 video game under the cooperative play style condition gave significantly more dimes to the other participant (M = 24.96, SD = 8.65) than participants who played the video game under the competitive play style condition (M = 18.67, SD = 8.32). The main effect for whether the video game was played face-to-face or online was not significant (F(1, 90) = 2.19, p {\textless} .05, partial η2 = ..024). Participants who played the video game face-to-face (M = 20.54, SD = 7.52) were not significantly different from participants who played the video game online (M = 23.28, SD = 10.25) in the number of dimes given. Finally, the interaction was not significant. Effects of participants' level of familiarity with one another and comparisons to past research on the effects of play style in video games is discussed.},
